Hi Ray,

I cannot begin to explain how much I love this.  Concerning the book
of John,

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
You wrote: &gt;**  &quot;Why couldn't several scribes have authored it ?&quot;  **
">

&quot;Is The Gospel According to John written in the first person?&quot; and
then you offered this information: **  Many biblical scholars think
that several scribes interviewed a number of people who heard John
speak and wrote down what they were told by the interviewees. This
helps to explain the syntax shifts.

I will try to answer your very good questions/observations.

There are several reasons I am convinced that the book of John is
written in the first person.  One example is found in John 4 when
Jesus Christ is speaking with the woman at the well.  John wrote:
6Jacob's well was there, and Jesus, tired as he was from the journey,
sat down by the well. It was about the sixth hour.  7When a Samaritan
woman came to draw water, Jesus said to her, &quot;Will you give me a
drink?&quot; 8(His disciples had gone into the town to buy food.)

This verse (among others) opens windows of understanding for different
records of this and the other gospels.  Many people look at this verse
and think that all of his disciples left to buy food but this is not
true.  John didn't say that all of Jesus' disciples had left only that
some of them had left.  At least two of them remained to capture the
event and one of them would have been John.  Perhaps the other was his
brother James.  As an example you are sitting sit at a table with many
of your friends and some of them leave.  An observer could truthfully
say that your friends left the table.  Look at everything in the book
of John written in parenthesis - these are verses added for
understanding.  Some explain events that happen later, some are
included later to explain the earlier events.  Some share intimate
information that only the person John wrote of would know and this
includes Jesus, Peter, and Judas Iscariot.

Another reason is this:  I understand from my studies that John was
Jesus' closest and dearest friend.  The omission of the events at the
garden of Gethsemane in the gospel of John would have been intentional
due to confidential information Jesus shared with John while Peter and
James slept.  Note in the other gospels that Jesus found his disciples
sleeping and reflect back on what I just shared about John 4:8.  Jesus
took his three closest chosen disciples with him to the garden to
pray.  Only two would have to be sleeping for their records to be
true.  Who would have given testimony of the events in the garden if
all of them had been asleep?  John witnessed the event, and Jesus
Christ validated his testimony.

I can see where Jesus gave John instructions to carry out after Jesus
was arrested and taken away.  The disciples would be frightened and
hurting and wouldn't understand and Jesus would have made this
provision for them.  John knew and understood who and what Jesus was
and he understood what had to take place.  After the resurrection
Jesus was truly the Son of God and yet the before his crucifixion and
physical death the Son of man truly needed a friend and confidant.  I
see that out of all of the Twelve, John was the most mature and I can
see that John was this friend.

There is so much more information contained within this book that has
been hidden since it was written.  John develops the character above
all of the other disciples for a very good reason.  In fact, the
character of Peter is portrayed in all of the gospels more than the
other disciples and John finishes the picture.  It helps us understand
the rest of the story.  I'll have to address some of the other reasons
later.  There's just too much to share in one post.

About the forgiveness of sins:  Jesus breathed into them the Holy
Spirit.  When He did this they became the first of His spiritual
brothers.  It is not man who forgives sins, it is the Spirit of God
that forgives the sins.  Before the resurection only Jesus was filled
with the Spirit.  It was through the disciples true belief in Jesus
Christ and their confession to others by their acts of emulating Jesus
Christ that He took their broken cisterns that could not hold water
and made them new.  When God filled them with His living water in Acts
2, their bodies held the water and it flowed from them out into the
world.

It is important to understand that these men were given a gift beyond
any other man before or after their time.  Jesus gave them his
authority and they had the understanding of the Spirit of God.  They
were filled with the Spirit of God just as Jesus Christ was - they
raised people from physical death and healed the injured, disabled and
sick.  These men did things through the power given to them by Jesus
Christ that no other men have done before or after them.  No man has
the authority to forgive sins, but the spiritual children of God
through their indwelling of the Holy Spirit do.

I need to stop for the moment.  I will get back to the rest of your
post shortly.  I want to share insight on the bread and water.

Shalom,
Ray

